This is a known breaking change. Android deprecated `SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE` (API 30), and .NET 10 MAUI adopted **edge-to-edge** rendering by default on Android, so `Resize` no longer triggers a layout change.

## Two options

### 1. Quick fix — use `Pan` mode

In your `MauiProgram.cs` or page code:

```csharp
using Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration;
using Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.AndroidSpecific;

// on your Page:
On<Android>().SetWindowSoftInputModeAdjust(
    WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Pan);
```

This scrolls the whole window up so the focused `Entry`/`Editor` stays visible. It works but you lose control over exactly what moves.

### 2. Recommended — react to keyboard insets (edge-to-edge)

Add a platform-specific handler in `Platforms/Android/` that listens for IME insets and adds bottom padding to your layout:

```csharp
// Platforms/Android/KeyboardInsetHelper.cs
using Android.Views;
using AndroidX.Core.View;
using Microsoft.Maui.Platform;

public static class KeyboardInsetHelper
{
    public static void Attach(Android.App.Activity activity, View rootView)
    {
        ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(rootView, new InsetListener());
    }

    private class InsetListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
    {
        public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
        {
            var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
            var navInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.NavigationBars());

            // Bottom padding = keyboard height (or nav bar if keyboard is closed)
            int bottom = Math.Max(imeInsets.Bottom, navInsets.Bottom);
            v.SetPadding(v.PaddingLeft, v.PaddingTop, v.PaddingRight, bottom);

            return insets;
        }
    }
}
```

Wire it up in `MainActivity.cs`:

```csharp
protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
{
    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);

    var rootView = Window!.DecorView.FindViewById(Android.Resource.Id.Content)!;
    KeyboardInsetHelper.Attach(this, rootView);
}
```

### Why option 2 is better for chat screens

| | Pan | Insets |
|---|---|---|
| Input bar slides up | ✅ | ✅ |
| Message list resizes | ❌ | ✅ |
| Works with `CollectionView` scroll-to-bottom | ❌ | ✅ |
| Fine-grained control | ❌ | ✅ |

With the insets approach your `CollectionView` shrinks to fit above the keyboard, so users can still scroll messages — exactly what chat apps expect.
